The Telegraph - Calcutta : Sports

 Thursday, June 16, 2005 

 Mumbai: The Asian snooker championship, which was to have been organised by the Maharashtra State Billiards and Snooker Association (MBSA) in Pune next month, has been called off due to lack of sponsors. ?We have been forced to call the meet off as we could not find a sponsor despite approaching 25 companies. It?s a shame none has come forward to sponsor this prestigious international event,? said MBSA joint secretary Derek Sippy. The meet has been shifted to Bangkok and will now be held from July 25-31. 

 New Delhi: The Indian junior hockey team left for Bilboe (Spain) on Wednesday for a four-nation tournament, which would be their final build-up event before embarking on the defence of the junior World Cup in Holland later this month. The 18-member team, led by Adrian D?Souza, will face Holland, Chile and hosts Spain in the June 17-19 event before heading to Germany for a week-long training camp and some practice matches. The Indians, who won the 2001 junior World Cup in Hobart, have just gone though an extensive 40-day camp in Hyderabad. 

 Wellington: Former All Blacks winger Jonah Lomu is to undergo surgery on a shoulder injury and will not play rugby again this season, dashing his hopes of completing a comeback after a kidney transplant. Lomu hurt his left shoulder playing in former England captain Martin Johnson?s testimonial match in London on June 4, his first competitive match in almost two years after receiving a new kidney last July. The 30-year-old had been named in a 27-man North Harbour squad to play Samoa in Albany on June 22.

 London: West Ham United have signed former Manchester United goalkeeper Roy Carroll, the promoted Premier League club said on Wednesday. The 27-year-old as released by Alex Ferguson after four years at Old Trafford, his last match for the club being the FA Cup final defeat by Arsenal in Cardiff. West Ham?s regular first-choice goalkeeper Jimmy Walker picked up a serious knee injury in the play-off final victory over Preston last month.

